            "texttype":"Online",
            "textpurpose":"Description",
            "textentryhtml":"<p>Two tomb figures that likely come from a much larger group. Each is comprises two sections: (1) painted head and glazed body down to the hem of the robe, (2) pedastal base and shoes up to the ankles. <br></p><p>Figure .1 stands with his hands draped with a wide amber cloth and held in front of his stomach. He wears a green robe and a black hat, and his hair falls to his shoulders in a fan across his back. The pedastal with the round-toe black boots should be paired with this figure. <br></p><p>Figure .2 stands with her (his?) hands draped with a small cloth and held in front of her stomach. She wears a green surcoat, amber sleeved robe, and red inner robe that is exposed at the hem. She wears a red crown with a front ornament, and her hair is tied in a topknot in the crown and also falls to the shoulders in a fan across his back. The pedastal with the pointed-toe shoes should be paired with this figure. <br></p><p>The green, amber, and cream glazes used for the figures’ clothes clearly evokes the famed three-color sancai glazes of the Tang dynasty (618-907).</p>",
            "remarks":null
        }
